const e={a1:"Imagery is more than decoration. It’s a powerful tool to help you communicate and differentiate your product.",a2:"Bold, graphic, and intentional imagery helps to engage the user.",a3:"Whether the mood is subdued and muted or bright and colorful, the following principles and best practices can help you successfully incorporate imagery and bring your apps to life, no matter what the visual brand.",a4:"Principles",a5:"Relevant",a6:"Informative",a7:"Delightful",a8:"Integrating with UI",a9:"Use appropriate resolution",a10:"Use scrims to protect text",a11:"Use cases",a12:"Avatars and thumbnails",a13:"Hero images",a14:"Galleries",a15:"Principles",a16:"Best practices",a17:"UI integration",a18:"When using illustration and photography to enhance the user experience, choose images that express personal relevance, information, and delight.",a19:"Personal relevance",a20:"Imagery can reflect the context and the world the user inhabits.",a21:"Information",a22:"Images can convey specific information that makes comprehension easy and immediate.",a23:"Delight",a24:"Portraying context with aesthetic beauty will make your product unique and add to user delight.",a25:"Appreciate context",a26:"Ensure images are dynamic and context-relevant. Use predictive visuals to substantially improve the user experience.",a27:"Use imagery that is context-relevant.",a28:"Be immersive",a29:"When necessary, it’s acceptable to obscure or allude to integrated heros and thumbnails through color and content overlays.",a30:"Background imagery can be obscured when engaging with foreground content.",a31:"Use multiple mediums",a32:"Both illustration and photography can live within the same product. Photography automatically implies a degree of specificity and should be used to showcase specific entities and stories. Illustration is effective for representing concepts and metaphors where specific photography might be alienating.",a33:"For specific entities, look first to photographic representation.",a34:"When total specificity is not available or applicable, illustration conveys approximation of content to aid comprehension.",a35:"Stay away from stock",a36:"Use imagery to express a distinctive voice and exemplify creative excellence.",a37:"For specific entities or branded content, use specific imagery. For more abstract content, be interpretive. Photographic stock and clipart is neither specific nor interpretive.",a38:"Strive for images that represent genuine stories.",a39:"Stock images can feel inauthentic.",a40:"For specific representations, use specific imagery.",a41:"Don't default to literal stock photography.",a42:"Have a point of focus",a43:"Have an iconic point of focus in your imagery. Focus ranges from a single entity to an overarching composition. Ensure that a clear concept is conveyed to the user in a memorable way.",a44:"Use color and composition to give images a clear focus.",a45:"Avoid making the user hunt for the meaning in the image.",a46:"The most powerful iconic images consist of a few meaningful elements, with minimal distractions.",a47:"When the point of focus is obscured, the iconic quality of the image is lost.",a48:"A clear focus communicates the concept at a glance.",a49:"A lack of focus makes the image meaningless.",a50:"Build narratives",a51:"Create an immersive story and a sense of context to humanize your app. Define the mood through visual storytelling. Is the mood aspirational? Somber? Celebratory?",a52:"An image that tells a story is infinitely more interesting and informative.",a53:"An image that lacks a story loses an opportunity to convey mood, brand, and context.",a54:"Properly contextualized concepts convey your message and brand more effectively.",a55:"A representation of an entity that is dissociated from context is uninteresting.",a56:"Resolution",a57:"Make sure your images are appropriately sized for displays and across platforms. Material design emphasizes large images. Ideally, the assets should not appear pixelated. Test appropriate resolution sizes for specific ratios and devices.",a58:"Appropriately sized imagery",a59:"Degraded imagery",a60:"Introduce scale",a61:"Introduce alternative scales to create levels of visual importance.",a62:"Within a gallery context, introduce thumbnails of various sizes to convey content hierarchy.",a63:"Encourage multiple containers living in the same ecosystem.",a64:"Text protection",a65:"To make typography legible on top of imagery, apply text protection in the form of <strong>scrims</strong> Scrims are lightweight, translucent material layers.",a66:"Dark end of gradient: Opacity values depend on context",a67:"Center point of gradient: 3/10ths closer the darker end",a68:"End point of gradient: Opacity of 0",a69:"To avoid banding (the formation of distinct stripe shapes), the gradient should be long, 3x standard app bar height, with the centerpoint about 3/10 towards the darker side of the gradient. This gives the gradient a natural falloff and avoids a sharp edge.",a70:"The gradient’s opacity should be chosen based on its environment. Some imagery can use darker gradients, such as the image displayed here with a 60% gradient.",a71:"Gradients could be as low as 10-20% in some contexts.",a72:"In this image, the gradient is 60% black.",a73:"This is the gradient which has been applied to the image at the left.",a74:"Dark scrims should ideally be between 20%-40% opacity depending on the content. Light scrims should ideally range from 40%-60% opacity depending on the content.",a75:"Don't obscure imagery when you use a scrim.",a76:"For larger real estate, target specific areas for text protection instead of blanketing the entire image.",a77:"Don’t ‘over-scrim’ large images.",a78:"Color overlays are different than text-protection scrims and can be used as a design element. When creating complementary color overlays, use the Palette API to define your color scheme based on content.",a79:"You can use your brand’s color palette decoratively to enhance imagery.",a80:"Avatars and thumbnails",a81:"Avatars and thumbnails represent entities or content, either literally through photography or conceptually through illustration. Generally, they are tap targets that lead to a primary view of the entity or content.",a82:"Avatars can be used to represent people. For personal avatars, offer personalization options. As users may choose not to personalize an avatar, provide delightful defaults. When used with a specific logo, avatars can also be used to represent brand.",a83:"Thumbnails allude to more information – letting the user peek into content – and assist navigation. Thumbnails let you include imagery in tight spaces.",a84:"Avatars make an app feel more personal – and occupy minimal space.",a85:"A brand avatar communicates information at a glance.",a86:"Hero images",a87:"Hero images are images that are usually anchored in a prominent position, above the fold, such as a banner at the top of the screen. They serve to draw in a user, provide context about the content, or reinforce the brand.",a88:"Related",a89:"Extract prominent colors from an image",a90:"Feature",a91:"A feature image is a bold, primary point of focus within a heterogeneous layout.",a92:"Integrated hero image",a93:"Integrated hero images create a setting for heterogeneous pieces of content within a layout. They are not the primary points of focus.",a94:"Gallery",a95:"Gallery images are bold visual hero images within homogenous layouts in either a grid or as a single image.",a96:"Photo Grid",a97:"Gallery image",a98:"Imagery in Material Design helps communicate your product",a99:"Material Design imagery reflects user context and environment",a100:"Images enhance understanding with Material Design concepts",a101:"Material Design: Unique beauty enhances user delight",a102:"Dynamic images enhance user experience in Material Design",a103:"Material Design: Use overlays to enhance immersion",a104:"Photographic representation for Material Design entities",a105:"Material Design illustration aids comprehension of content",a106:"Authentic images reflecting Material Design stories",a107:"Authentic images in Material Design",a108:"Use specific imagery for Material Design elements",a109:"Avoid using generic stock photos in Material Design",a110:"Material Design: Use color for clear image focus",a111:"Material Design: Avoid user confusion with clear imagery",a112:"Powerful Material Design elements with minimal distractions",a113:"Material Design: Maintain focus for clarity and impact",a114:"Material Design: Clear focus for instant understanding",a115:"Meaningless image due to lack of focus in Material Design",a116:"Material Design: A story-telling image that informs",a117:"Material Design: Images should tell a story and convey context",a118:"Material Design enhances message and brand clarity.",a119:"Material Design: Entity representation lacks context",a120:"Appropriately sized imagery in Material Design",a121:"Degraded imagery with Material Design elements",a122:"Material Design thumbnails of varying sizes for hierarchy",a123:"Material Design: Support for multiple containers ecosystem",a124:"Text protection with scrims for Material Design readability",a125:"60% black gradient in Material Design style",a126:"Gradient applied to the image using Material Design",a127:"Material Design: Dark scrims 20%-40%, light scrims 40%-60%",a128:"Material Design: Avoid obscuring imagery with scrims",a129:"Material Design: Target areas for text protection",a130:"Material Design: Avoid over-scrimming large images",a131:"Color overlays in Material Design using the Palette API",a132:"Use your brand colors in Material Design to enhance imagery",a133:"Material Design avatars add a personal touch with minimal space",a134:"Material Design avatar conveying information quickly",a135:"Material Design Android icon",a136:"Material Design feature image for bold focus in layout",a137:"Integrated hero image in Material Design for diverse content layout",a138:"Material Design Photo Grid",a139:"Gallery image with Material Design style"};export{e as en};
